StatefulSets (3:47 - 4:10)

A StatefulSet is a specialized Kubernetes workload object used to manage stateful applications.

Unlike a Deployment, which treats Pods as interchangeable and replaceable, a StatefulSet maintains a sticky identity for each of its Pods
[3]. These Pods are created from the same spec but are not interchangeable; each keeps a persistent identifier across any rescheduling [3].

Key Characteristics

Stable Network IDs: Pods get unique, predictable names like mysql-0, mysql-1, and mysql-2 [3]. They keep these names even if they crash and
restart on a different node.
Stable Persistent Storage: Each Pod gets its own unique persistent disk volume [3]. If mysql-1 fails and restarts, it automatically 
reconnects to its exact same data volume.
Ordered Deployment: Pods are created, updated, and deleted in a strict, sequential order (from 0 to N-1) [3].

Common Use Cases
StatefulSets are designed for complex systems that require data consistency and coordination:
Relational Databases: Systems like MySQL, PostgreSQL, or SQL Server.
NoSQL Databases: Distributed databases like MongoDB, Cassandra, or Redis clusters.
Distributed Services: Applications like Apache Kafka, ZooKeeper, or Elasticsearch that need fixed cluster cluster roles.

YAML Manifest Example
A StatefulSet requires a Headless Service (a Service with clusterIP: None) to manage the network identities of the individual Pods [3]. 
It also uses a volumeClaimTemplates block to automatically provision a unique disk for each Pod.

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: nginx-headless
  labels:
    app: nginx
spec:
  ports:
  - port: 80
    name: web
  clusterIP: None       # 🌐 Headless service for stable DNS names
  selector:
    app: nginx
---
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: StatefulSet
metadata:
  name: web-stateful
spec:
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: nginx
  serviceName: "nginx-headless"
  replicas: 3
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: nginx
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx
        image: registry.k8s.io/nginx-slim:0.24
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
          name: web
        volumeMounts:
        - name: www
          mountPath: /usr/share/nginx/html
  volumeClaimTemplates: # 💾 Automatically creates a unique PVC for every Pod
  - metadata:
      name: www
    spec:
      accessModes: [ "ReadWriteOnce" ]
      resources:
        requests:
          storage: 1Gi

Crucial Storage Behavior
When a StatefulSet is scaled down or deleted, Kubernetes will not delete the associated Persistent Volume Claims (PVCs) or data volumes.
This is a safety feature designed to prevent accidental data loss. If you want to clean up the storage, you must delete the PVCs manually
using kubectl delete pvc.

Config Maps (4:11 - 4:18)

A ConfigMap is an API object used to store non-confidential data in key-value pairs.It allows you to separate your configuration settings
from your application code. This means you can build your container image once and change the configuration settings for different 
environments (like development, staging, or production) without rebuilding the image.

ConfigMaps vs. Secrets
ConfigMaps are for plain-text, public configuration data. Examples include application ports, configuration files, or feature flags.
Secrets are for sensitive data. Examples include passwords, API keys, or SSH keys. Secrets are stored securely (obfuscated or encrypted).

Common Ways to Use a ConfigMap
Your application containers can use a ConfigMap in three main ways:

Environment Variables: Injecting keys as environment variables straight into the container.
Command-Line Arguments: Passing values into the container startup command.
Data Volume Files: Mounting the ConfigMap as a folder of configuration files inside the container.

YAML Manifest Example
This example shows a ConfigMap storing two configuration keys, and a Pod that pulls those keys in as environment variables.

apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: app-settings
data:
  ui_color: "blue"             # 🎨 Simple key-value pair
  max_connections: "100"      # ⚙️ Simple configuration value
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: backend-pod
spec:
  containers:
  - name: web-app
    image: nginx:latest
    env:
    - name: THEME_COLOR        # 📥 Creates an environment variable in the container
      valueFrom:
        configMapKeyRef:
          name: app-settings   # Looks at the ConfigMap above
          key: ui_color        # Pulls the value "blue"
    - name: MAX_CONN
      valueFrom:
        configMapKeyRef:
          name: app-settings
          key: max_connections

Useful Commands

You can create and check ConfigMaps directly from your terminal:

Create from a file: kubectl create configmap my-config --from-file=app.properties
Create from literal values: kubectl create configmap UI-config --from-literal=color=blue
View the configuration data: kubectl get configmap app-settings -o yaml

Secrets (Video 4:10 - 4:32)

A Secret is an API object used to store and manage sensitive information.It lets you save data like passwords, API keys, and tokens safely
without putting them directly into your application code or container images [1].

ConfigMaps vs. Secrets
ConfigMaps store plain-text, non-confidential configuration data (like app settings or theme colors).
Secrets store sensitive data. By default, Kubernetes stores Secret data as Base64 encoded strings.

Important: Base64 encoding is not encryption. Anyone with access to the file or cluster can easily decode it. You should always use extra
security controls, like encryption at rest, to fully secure your Secrets.

Common Ways to Use a Secret
Just like ConfigMaps, your containers can use Secrets in two main ways:
Environment Variables: Injecting the secret data directly into the application environment.
Volume Mounts: Mounting the secret as a file inside a secure, temporary folder in the container.

YAML Manifest Example
This example shows a Secret holding a database password, and a Pod that reads that password using an environment variable.

apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata:
  name: db-credentials
type: Opaque               # Standard type for arbitrary user-defined data
data:
  password: cGFzc3dvcmQxMjM= # 🔒 The string "password123" encoded in Base64
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: app-pod
spec:
  containers:
  - name: my-app
    image: nginx:latest
    env:
    - name: DATABASE_PASSWORD
      valueFrom:
        secretKeyRef:
          name: db-credentials # Looks at the Secret above
          key: password        # Pulls the decoded value into the container

Useful Commands
You can create Secrets quickly using the command line without writing out the Base64 values by hand:

Create from literal values: kubectl create secret generic db-credentials --from-literal=password=password123
Create from a file: kubectl create secret generic ssh-key-secret --from-file=~/.ssh/id_rsa
View the Secret: kubectl get secret db-credentials -o yaml
